    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm seeing a weird 500 error on our /api/v1/checkout/complete endpoint. It only happens intermittently, usually when there's high traffic. Here is a snippet from the logs during one of the crashes:\n\n[2023-10-27 14:22:01] ERROR: ConnectionTimeout during inventory_update_service call. \n[2023-10-27 14:22:01] ERROR: Failed to acquire lock on resource: db_transaction_lock_442.\n[2023-10-27 14:22:02] CRITICAL: Deadlock detected in transaction pool.\n[2023-10-27 14:22:02] FATAL: Internal Server Error - unexpected state in state_machine_v2.\n\nCan you look at this and tell me what's likely causing the instability?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It appears that you're experiencing a common scenario during high-traffic periods where concurrent transactions are causing issues. The \"ConnectionTimeout\" and the failure to acquire a lock on the `db_transaction_lock_442` suggest that your database server is struggling with handling simultaneous requests. The \"Deadlock detected in transaction pool\" line is a strong indicator that transactions are waiting on each other to release locks, resulting in a deadlock. The \"Internal Server Error\" contrasts with these clues and suggests a complex error within the state machine, possibly due to transaction rollback or an error context that isn't directly related to the deadlock and locked resource. Investigating the state machine implementation and improving your transaction handling mechanism might stabilize your API endpoint during peak traffic. Consider implementing better lock management, query optimization, or scaling your database resources to handle concurrent loads more effectively.",
